Things have stabilized quite a bit with the score rebuild, though not 100% perfect yet. However, it is close enough that I am inclined to **Not** reset the whole thing, just need a bit more time to get everything solid

Our team has been swamped with other projects the past few weeks, but next week we will start on a series of improvements to the website for further transparency on each scoring data point. 

Miners should be aware that the entropy score is now much more consistent, because I moved the storage to the DB instead of a JSON file. What this means is that score will be more heavily impacted by copy trading or running the same strategy across multiple miners. The more similar a bet is to an existing bet, the greater the penalty to score. Similarity is measured by wager amount, timing, odds, etc. So whoever keeps placing hundreds of 1 dollar wagers for the same outcome/odds, that strategy is going to be less effective now lol. ( not that it was that effective in the first place - virtually equivalent score to a single higher wager)

In the near future, I will be increasing the weight to the entropy score further, so as to strongly discourage copy betting or running the same exact strategy across multiple hotkeys. If you want to farm incentive, you've got to at least contribute unique data (looking at the people running 15+ keys all with the same predictions)

For those that keep sending me score comparisons like "hey this guy didnt make better predictions today but he has higher incentive, why is everything broken?":

In the majority of those cases, it's because that key had a long, solid history of decent performance and had a bad day or two. The higher the tier, the less a single day's performance will impact score. Wondering why 3 good bets in a single day didn't significantly impact your score? Same reason. By tier 3, the scoring window is a **15 day** rolling average.

If it's not that, the other cases are mostly because there is always going to be *some* inconsistency between validators, no matter how many things we implement to prevent that. Even with syncing, auto updates, etc. 
We have validators that weight copy, we have "hybrid validators" (those that run the code, but still use some element of weight copying/averaging to keep their vtrust high through instability), we have maybe 3 that are actually just purely running our code, and we have our team validator, which is the "source of truth" for syncing and auto updating.
Between all of those, we have some amount of non determinism that results in fluctuations to the final consensus score.

Since implementing sync, I'd say about 90% of keys are consistently ranked in accordance with their actual composite score, and the other 10% are still quite close to where they should be. Obviously we have days of instability when we need to push major changes or fixes, but generally speaking , if your key has a certain incentive, you should expect that it is a pretty solid representation of your current performance relative to other miners. 

The remaining keys that are still at 0 are mostly all brand new keys, with maybe a few exceptions. I will need some more time to make sure everything is fixed before I drop registration again, and will keep everyone posted here

The main change i made in the scoring system (besides fixing bugs) is that instead of scoring on the avg of all non-zero days in the window, we now count the 0 days as well. This caused quite a reshuffling of scores in some cases, but composite scores and weights more accurately reflect performance over the current tier window relative to other miners, as originally intended.

Weights structure was also adjusted, meaning that tier 1 miners will have very low incentive. It's not until tier 2 and higher that incentive starts to be meaningful. This is in line with what we want- only the top 10-20% of miners are even profitable at all over the long term
I will be experimenting with weight curve over the coming week to align as best as possible with only rewarding profitable miners

I understand that this may be upsetting to those who have gotten incentive for participation, but we are ramping up quality and we do not care about a days or weeks worth of good predictions - that data is meaningless without demonstratable long term performance

All that said, we are still waiting on a better sync between all validators. Weight copiers/hybrid valis cause this to happen more slowly than we'd like, and there's not much we can do about that without a more complicated sync feature (which is planned and being designed)

the next steps for us are a better dashboard for miners, so they can analyze their current performance relative to others in their tier.  And then we will be moving towards productizing our data as a service to anyone, meaning that it could eventually become another source of revenue for top miners (and validators that actually do the work, once we can solve the WC issue)
